MALAYSIA DAYBOOK: Maxis Profit May Rise, New Bursa Chief Named

-- B y   B a r r y   P o r t e r
-- 
2011-02-27T22:14:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-27/malaysia-daybook-maxis-profit-may-rise-new-bursa-chief-named.html
Maxis Bhd.,  Malaysia ’s biggest mobile
phone company, will announce fourth-quarter earnings after 5 p.m.
It’s likely to report a 19 percent increase in net income to
596.2 million ringgit in the three months ended Dec. 31,
compared with 503 million ringgit a year ago, according to the
median estimate of five analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News.  EQUITY PREVIEW:
* Bursa Malaysia Bhd. (BURSA MK): The country’s stock exchange
operator said RHB Capital Bhd. Group Managing Director Tajuddin
Atan will replace Yusli Mohamed Yusoff as its chief executive
officer from April 1.
* CIMB Group Holdings Bhd. (CIMB MK): Malaysia’s second-biggest
lender by market value said fourth-quarter profit rose 9.3
percent to 877.6 million ringgit, helping it plan a record
dividend payout.
* DRB-Hicom Bhd. (DRB MK): The auto group said third-quarter net
income rose to 110.1 million ringgit from 103.5 million ringgit
a year ago.
* Malaysia Building Society Bhd. (MBS MK): The mortgage
financier said it will issue five rights shares for every seven
held.
* Malaysian Airline System Bhd. (MAS MK): The national carrier
said its profit more than halved in the fourth quarter to 225.9
million ringgit after making smaller gains on derivatives
hedging as oil prices rise.
* MMC Bhd. (MMC MK): Malaysia’s biggest builder said it is
considering options for its power unit, Malakoff Corp.,
including a possible share-sale.
* PLUS Expressways Bhd. (PLUS MK): Malaysia’s biggest toll-road
operator said fourth-quarter profit rose to 337.8 million
ringgit from 315 million ringgit a year earlier.
* SP Setia Bhd. (SPSB MK): The developer said it expects to
raise 1.2 billion ringgit through its placement, subject to
demand. The company is targeting 3 billion ringgit in sales this
financial year, it said in a statement.
* Telekom Malaysia Bhd. (T MK): The national fixed-line phone
and internet company said fourth-quarter net income rose to
400.6 million ringgit from 170.3 million ringgit a year earlier,
boosted by higher sales.  MARKETS ON FEB 25:
* Malaysia’s FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI Index was little-changed.
* The MSCI Asia Pacific Index increased 1 percent.
* The  Dow Jones Industrial Average  gained 0.5 percent.
* Palm oil May-delivery futures advanced 1.7 percent to 3,515
ringgit ($1,152) a metric ton.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Barry Porter in  Kuala Lumpur  at 
